result.execSummary:
The defendant Kennesha R. Funmaker was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: If probation is revoked and a prison term is not ordered, or if probation is discharged or terminated, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of any restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.

Defendant must attend and successfully complete an alcohol assessment and comply with any recommended treatment, if agent recommends.  Defendant is to execute any releases necessary for agent to verify compliance.

Defendant must attend and successfully complete a drug assessment, and comply with any recommended treatment, if agent recommends.  Defendant to execute any releases necessary for agent to verify compliance.

Defendant shall have no contact, directly or indirectly, either personally, by mail, telephone or through any other person, with the victim, their workplace, home or anywhere they are located.  Defendant to write a letter of apology to the victim, to be pre-approved by her agent.

Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle on the highways until properly licensed.  Defendant to obtain her driver's license during the term of probation.

The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.

Defendant to undergo anger management counseling and comply with any recommended treatment, if agent recommends.

Defendant shall not consume any alcohol unless a physician states in writing that the defendant is alcohol dependent and complete withdrawal could endanger the defendant's health or life. In this case a doctor's excuse must be submitted to the Jackson County Clerk of Court or the Jackson County Jail within 48 hours of the bond being signed. Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located. Upon request, the defendant shall appear for and submit to testing within two (2) hours of the official's request.
